window.SLIDES = [{"index":1,"group":1,"section":1,"gnum":1,"mega":1,"chapter":1,"colorKey":1,"shadeStep":0,"folder":"Mg01_g01_01_RC","name":"RC","items":[{"type":"image","name":"Doreen_004_Simondon-1-1024x682.jpg","src":"/Slides_Datasets/Mg01_g01_01_RC/Doreen_004_Simondon-1-1024x682.jpg"},{"type":"image","name":"ill_4378846_26a6_simondon_x1p1 (1).png","src":"/Slides_Datasets/Mg01_g01_01_RC/ill_4378846_26a6_simondon_x1p1%20%281%29.png"},{"type":"text","name":"intro.txt","text":"In his essay on Du mode d'existence des objets techniques (1958), \r\nSchmidgen traces Simondon’s thinking through three distinct movements\r\nThis results in an intellectual journey that resonates remarkably well \r\nwith the current relationship between AI and architecture.\r\n\r\nWhen discussing machines, or technical objects, as Simondon calls them\r\nwe often ask: What do we want from machines? \r\nToday, the same question is repeatedly posed to AI. \r\n\r\nYet a more fundamental question is rarely considered:"}]},{"index":2,"group":1,"section":1,"gnum":1,"mega":1,"chapter":1,"colorKey":1,"shadeStep":0,"folder":"Mg01_g01_02_RC","name":"RC","items":[{"type":"text","name":"pop_up.txt","text":"What does the machine want?"}]},{"index":3,"group":1,"section":1,"gnum":1,"mega":1,"chapter":1,"colorKey":1,"shadeStep":0,"folder":"Mg01_g01_03_RC","name":"RC","items":[{"type":"carousel","name":"01–06","frames":[{"src":"/Slides_Datasets/Mg01_g01_03_RC/01.png","name":"01.png"},{"src":"/Slides_Datasets/Mg01_g01_03_RC/02.png","name":"02.png"},{"src":"/Slides_Datasets/Mg01_g01_03_RC/03.png","name":"03.png"},{"src":"/Slides_Datasets/Mg01_g01_03_RC/04.png","name":"04.png"},{"src":"/Slides_Datasets/Mg01_g01_03_RC/05.png","name":"05.png"},{"src":"/Slides_Datasets/Mg01_g01_03_RC/06.png","name":"06.png"}]},{"type":"text","name":"explicacion.txt","text":"before answering that question, let us first look at these\r\ntechnical objects that surround us every day.\r\n\r\nA watch. \r\nA radio.\r\nA light bulb. \r\nA camera \r\nEven the electric toothbrush you used this morning.\r\n\r\nTake a moment to consider them. \r\n\r\nThey are so familiar that we rarely notice them anymore.\r\nNow, looking at these objects, ask yourself:\r\n"}]},{"index":4,"group":1,"section":1,"gnum":1,"mega":1,"chapter":1,"colorKey":1,"shadeStep":0,"folder":"Mg01_g01_04_RC","name":"RC","items":[{"type":"text","name":"pop_up.txt","text":"Do you actually want to understand these objects?\r\n\r\nOr do you simply ignore them, taking them for granted as long as they continue to function?\r\n"}]},{"index":1,"group":2,"section":1,"gnum":2,"mega":1,"chapter":2,"colorKey":1,"shadeStep":1,"folder":"Mg01_g02_01_RC","name":"RC","items":[{"type":"text","name":"intro.txt","text":"In a state of ignorance, technical objects appear to us as black boxes. \r\n\r\nWe do not understand their internal processes, their logic, or their evolution.\r\nWe simply see the input and the output, they seem almost magical, \r\nquietly producing exactly the result we need while \r\n\r\nSimondon does not simply describe this as a lack of knowledge, \r\nthis ignorance, or avoidance is actually can be seen through two different ways\r\n\r\nLets look into those images:"},{"type":"video","name":"Le Chant du Styrène 1958.mp4","src":"/Slides_Datasets/Mg01_g02_01_RC/Le%20Chant%20du%20Styr%C3%A8ne%201958.mp4"}]},{"index":2,"group":2,"section":1,"gnum":2,"mega":1,"chapter":2,"colorKey":1,"shadeStep":1,"folder":"Mg01_g02_02_RC","name":"RC","items":[{"type":"image","name":"Citroen_DS_19.jpg","src":"/Slides_Datasets/Mg01_g02_02_RC/Citroen_DS_19.jpg"},{"type":"video","name":"Grabación 2026-06-03 052525.mp4","src":"/Slides_Datasets/Mg01_g02_02_RC/Grabaci%C3%B3n%202026-06-03%20052525.mp4"},{"type":"image","name":"im-406803.avif","src":"/Slides_Datasets/Mg01_g02_02_RC/im-406803.avif"},{"type":"text","name":"intro.txt","text":"What do you see?\r\nBy Barthes the Cytroen seems as a Goddess\r\n\r\nRespected, worshipped, almost sacred\r\n\r\nother example include, the last iphone release or most recently the AP x Swatch collaboration"},{"type":"image","name":"new.jpg","src":"/Slides_Datasets/Mg01_g02_02_RC/new.jpg"}]},{"index":3,"group":2,"section":1,"gnum":2,"mega":1,"chapter":2,"colorKey":1,"shadeStep":1,"folder":"Mg01_g02_03_RC","name":"RC","items":[{"type":"image","name":"image (45).png","src":"/Slides_Datasets/Mg01_g02_03_RC/image%20%2845%29.png"},{"type":"image","name":"image (46).png","src":"/Slides_Datasets/Mg01_g02_03_RC/image%20%2846%29.png"},{"type":"text","name":"intro.txt","text":"and now let's look at\r\n\r\nIn the case of AI, data centers, and computational infrastructure \r\nare often kept far from view, almost invisible to the people who use them every day.\r\n\r\nThis is where Simondon identifies two opposite yet \r\nclosely related ways of avoiding a genuine understanding of technical objects.\r\n\r\nWe either ignore them completely, treating them as black boxes whose inner workings do not concern us.\r\n\r\nOr we elevate them to something almost mythical, attributing to them powers they do not actually possess.\r\n\r\nIn both cases, the result is the same: we fail to understand the machine itself. \r\n\r\nWe either dismiss it or worship it, but rarely do we engage with it\r\n\r\n\r\nwhich bring us to our next relevation"}]},{"index":4,"group":2,"section":1,"gnum":2,"mega":1,"chapter":2,"colorKey":1,"shadeStep":1,"folder":"Mg01_g02_04_RC","name":"RC","items":[{"type":"text","name":"intro.txt","text":"It is not humanity that has become enslaved to machines.\r\n\r\nThe machines have been reduced to the status of servants\r\n\r\nsubordinated entirely to human needs and desires. \r\n\r\nas we continue being completely different to what they are"}]},{"index":1,"group":3,"section":1,"gnum":3,"mega":1,"chapter":3,"colorKey":1,"shadeStep":2,"folder":"Mg01_g03_01_RC","name":"RC","items":[{"type":"image","name":"4-Figure1-1.png","src":"/Slides_Datasets/Mg01_g03_01_RC/4-Figure1-1.png"},{"type":"image","name":"images.png","src":"/Slides_Datasets/Mg01_g03_01_RC/images.png"},{"type":"text","name":"intro.txt","text":"To understand this let's bring it to an example:\r\n\r\nas we have del campo with us today let's bring it to AI\r\n\r\nLet's take a look at the Robot Garden\r\n\r\nan outdoor garden at the University of Michigan's Robotics building, inaugurated in 2021\r\n\r\nIt is revolutionary because the design of the ground and the textures of the garden were not \r\ndesigned by an architect sitting with a mouse. \r\n\r\nWhat they did was take satellite images of the terrain, train a neural network with thousands \r\nof images of architectural elements \r\n\r\nand then let the network dream those elements onto the image of the site.\r\n\r\n\r\n"},{"type":"image","name":"SPAN_Robot_Garden_hills_1.webp","src":"/Slides_Datasets/Mg01_g03_01_RC/SPAN_Robot_Garden_hills_1.webp"}]},{"index":2,"group":3,"section":1,"gnum":3,"mega":1,"chapter":3,"colorKey":1,"shadeStep":2,"folder":"Mg01_g03_02_RC","name":"RC","items":[{"type":"text","name":"intro.txt","text":"When Ai designs a building, something weird and intersting happens, \r\nand it is too weird and intersting that is worth be taken seriously rather than dismissing\r\n\r\nThe result is a landscape that looks natural but has a strange artificiality. \r\nThe forms are not what a human would have chosen. \r\nThey are what a machine saw when it tried to see architecture in an empty terrain.\r\n\r\nwhich leads us to our next chapter:"},{"type":"image","name":"SPAN_Robot_Garden_hills_1.webp","src":"/Slides_Datasets/Mg01_g03_02_RC/SPAN_Robot_Garden_hills_1.webp"},{"type":"image","name":"SPAN_Robot_Garden_Photo_02.webp","src":"/Slides_Datasets/Mg01_g03_02_RC/SPAN_Robot_Garden_Photo_02.webp"},{"type":"image","name":"SPAN_Robot_Garden_Photo_05-360x243.webp","src":"/Slides_Datasets/Mg01_g03_02_RC/SPAN_Robot_Garden_Photo_05-360x243.webp"},{"type":"image","name":"SPAN_Robot_Garden_Photo_08-360x243.webp","src":"/Slides_Datasets/Mg01_g03_02_RC/SPAN_Robot_Garden_Photo_08-360x243.webp"},{"type":"image","name":"SPAN_Robot_Garden_Rendering_08.webp","src":"/Slides_Datasets/Mg01_g03_02_RC/SPAN_Robot_Garden_Rendering_08.webp"}]},{"index":3,"group":3,"section":1,"gnum":3,"mega":1,"chapter":3,"colorKey":1,"shadeStep":2,"folder":"Mg01_g03_03_RC","name":"RC","items":[{"type":"text","name":"intro.txt","text":"What If we Open the black box?"}]},{"index":1,"group":4,"section":2,"gnum":1,"mega":2,"chapter":1,"colorKey":2,"shadeStep":0,"folder":"Mg02_g01_01_Creative_AI","name":"Creative AI","items":[{"type":"image","name":"Ferrari_AI.jpg","src":"/Slides_Datasets/Mg02_g01_01_Creative_AI/Ferrari_AI.jpg"},{"type":"text","name":"note.txt","text":"CAN AI BE CREATIVE? CAN AI CREATE SOMETHING NEW?\r\n\r\nThere is always the question of whether something truly new can emerge from a dataset of existing designs.\r\n\r\nFull electric Ferrari using GenAI (Image by Arturo Tedeschi)\r\n"}]},{"index":2,"group":4,"section":2,"gnum":1,"mega":2,"chapter":1,"colorKey":2,"shadeStep":0,"folder":"Mg02_g01_02_Something_Different","name":"Something Different","items":[{"type":"image","name":"2026-06-02_20260602_185245_output_00001_.png","src":"/Slides_Datasets/Mg02_g01_02_Something_Different/2026-06-02_20260602_185245_output_00001_.png"},{"type":"text","name":"note.txt","text":"A NEUROSCIENTIST LOOKING FOR SOMETHING DIFFERENT NOT NEW\r\n\r\nHow to design a modern residential home using methods that combine insights from neuroscience with combinational design methodologies?\r\n"}]},{"index":1,"group":5,"section":2,"gnum":2,"mega":2,"chapter":2,"colorKey":2,"shadeStep":1,"folder":"Mg02_g02_01_Deep_House","name":"Deep House","items":[{"type":"image","name":"Deep_House.png","src":"/Slides_Datasets/Mg02_g02_01_Deep_House/Deep_House.png"},{"type":"image","name":"exterior3_edit.webp","src":"/Slides_Datasets/Mg02_g02_01_Deep_House/exterior3_edit.webp"},{"type":"image","name":"Screenshot 2026-06-02 201409.png","src":"/Slides_Datasets/Mg02_g02_01_Deep_House/Screenshot%202026-06-02%20201409.png"}]},{"index":2,"group":5,"section":2,"gnum":2,"mega":2,"chapter":2,"colorKey":2,"shadeStep":1,"folder":"Mg02_g02_02_About_Creativity","name":"About Creativity","items":[{"type":"image","name":"Margaret_Boden.jpg","src":"/Slides_Datasets/Mg02_g02_02_About_Creativity/Margaret_Boden.jpg"},{"type":"text","name":"note.txt","text":"MATIAS DEL CAMPO\r\n\r\nArchitect, designer and educator.\r\nCo-founder of SPAN in Vienna in 2003.\r\n"}]},{"index":1,"group":6,"section":2,"gnum":3,"mega":2,"chapter":3,"colorKey":2,"shadeStep":2,"folder":"Mg02_g03_01_Matias_del_Campo","name":"Matias del Campo","items":[{"type":"image","name":"Matias del Campo.jpg","src":"/Slides_Datasets/Mg02_g03_01_Matias_del_Campo/Matias%20del%20Campo.jpg"},{"type":"text","name":"note.txt","text":"MATIAS DEL CAMPO\r\n\r\nArchitect, designer and educator.\r\nCo-founder of of the architecture practice SPAN (Vienna, 2003)\r\n"},{"type":"image","name":"SPAN_Architecture_design_Logo.webp","src":"/Slides_Datasets/Mg02_g03_01_Matias_del_Campo/SPAN_Architecture_design_Logo.webp"}]},{"index":2,"group":6,"section":2,"gnum":3,"mega":2,"chapter":3,"colorKey":2,"shadeStep":2,"folder":"Mg02_g03_02_Citroen_DS_19","name":"Citroen DS 19","items":[{"type":"image","name":"Citroen DS 19 (Salon de l'Automobil  1955).jpg","src":"/Slides_Datasets/Mg02_g03_02_Citroen_DS_19/Citroen%20DS%2019%20%28Salon%20de%20l%27Automobil%20%201955%29.jpg"},{"type":"image","name":"Citroen_DS_19.jpg","src":"/Slides_Datasets/Mg02_g03_02_Citroen_DS_19/Citroen_DS_19.jpg"},{"type":"image","name":"new.jpg","src":"/Slides_Datasets/Mg02_g03_02_Citroen_DS_19/new.jpg"},{"type":"text","name":"note.txt","text":"CITROEN DS AS A GODDESS\r\n\r\n\r\n"}]},{"index":3,"group":6,"section":2,"gnum":3,"mega":2,"chapter":3,"colorKey":2,"shadeStep":2,"folder":"Mg02_g03_03_Church_AI","name":"Church AI","items":[{"type":"image","name":"5-Figure2-1.png","src":"/Slides_Datasets/Mg02_g03_03_Church_AI/5-Figure2-1.png"},{"type":"image","name":"6-Figure5-1.png","src":"/Slides_Datasets/Mg02_g03_03_Church_AI/6-Figure5-1.png"},{"type":"image","name":"The Church of AI.jpg","src":"/Slides_Datasets/Mg02_g03_03_Church_AI/The%20Church%20of%20AI.jpg"}]},{"index":1,"group":7,"section":3,"gnum":1,"mega":4,"chapter":1,"colorKey":4,"shadeStep":0,"folder":"Mg04_g01_01_Conductor_Not_Brush","name":"Conductor Not Brush","items":[{"type":"image","name":"image_10.png","src":"/Slides_Datasets/Mg04_g01_01_Conductor_Not_Brush/image_10.png"},{"type":"text","name":"note.txt","text":"THE CONDUCTOR\n\nMatias del Campo is not an artist who uses AI as a brush.\nHe is a conductor.\n\nThe AI is not the instrument.\nThe instrument is the whole relationship.\n"}]},{"index":2,"group":7,"section":3,"gnum":1,"mega":4,"chapter":1,"colorKey":4,"shadeStep":0,"folder":"Mg04_g01_02_Orchestra_Quote","name":"Orchestra Quote","items":[{"type":"text","name":"note.txt","text":"\"Far from being the supervisor of a squad of slaves, man is the permanent organizer of a society of technical objects which need him as much as musicians in an orchestra need a conductor.\"\n\n— Gilbert Simondon\n"}]},{"index":1,"group":8,"section":3,"gnum":2,"mega":4,"chapter":2,"colorKey":4,"shadeStep":1,"folder":"Mg04_g02_01_The_Instrument","name":"The Instrument","items":[{"type":"text","name":"note.txt","text":"THE INSTRUMENT IS THE RELATIONSHIP\n\nNo single player makes the music. The orchestra is:\n\n· HUMAN INTENTION — the question being asked\n· DATASET — the memory the machine was trained on\n· LATENT SPACE — the field of everything it could imagine\n· SELECTION — the human ear, choosing what matters\n· MATERIAL OUTPUT — form, finally made real\n\nThe conductor plays none of these.\nHe plays the space between them.\n"}]},{"index":2,"group":8,"section":3,"gnum":2,"mega":4,"chapter":2,"colorKey":4,"shadeStep":1,"folder":"Mg04_g02_02_Listens","name":"Listens","items":[{"type":"text","name":"note.txt","text":"THE CONDUCTOR DOES NOT DOMINATE. THE CONDUCTOR LISTENS.\n\nFor Simondon, the good technician is not the master of a squad of slaves.\nHe keeps each machine's margin of indetermination open — attending,\nadjusting, interpreting, never fully automating.\n\nTo conduct is to listen: to hold the ensemble together\nwithout silencing any of its voices.\n"}]},{"index":1,"group":9,"section":3,"gnum":3,"mega":4,"chapter":3,"colorKey":4,"shadeStep":2,"folder":"Mg04_g03_01_Situated_Inference","name":"Situated Inference","items":[{"type":"text","name":"note.txt","text":"DESIGN AS SITUATED INFERENCE\n\nIn del Campo's \"Intersections\" paper, creativity is not a metaphysical spark\nbut an INFERENTIAL process — ideation, evaluation, and contextual negotiation\ndistributed across human, machine, and material.\n\nThe architect becomes a MEDIATOR:\nselecting, interpreting, and translating the model's statistical relations\ninto cultural and spatial propositions.\n"}]},{"index":2,"group":9,"section":3,"gnum":3,"mega":4,"chapter":3,"colorKey":4,"shadeStep":2,"folder":"Mg04_g03_02_Noise_To_Form","name":"Noise To Form","items":[{"type":"text","name":"note.txt","text":"FROM NOISE TO COHERENCE\n\nGANs, diffusion models, transformers —\ntheir iterative transformation from noise to form\nmakes the inferential logic visible.\n\nThey do not imitate creativity.\nThey expose its structure: feedback, calibration, emergence.\n"}]},{"index":3,"group":9,"section":3,"gnum":3,"mega":4,"chapter":3,"colorKey":4,"shadeStep":2,"folder":"Mg04_g03_03_Relational","name":"Relational","items":[{"type":"text","name":"note.txt","text":"CREATIVITY IS RELATIONAL\n\nNot a spark inside one mind, but a posthuman ecology:\nintelligence that is relational, procedural, and materially embedded.\n\nReasoning emerges from the recursive interplay of many agents —\nhuman, synthetic, and environmental — sharing one ecology\nof information, matter, and meaning.\n"}]},{"index":1,"group":10,"section":3,"gnum":4,"mega":4,"chapter":4,"colorKey":4,"shadeStep":3,"folder":"Mg04_g04_01_Representatives","name":"Representatives","items":[{"type":"text","name":"note.txt","text":"A SEAT FOR THE TECHNICAL OBJECT\n\nSimondon called for representatives of technical beings —\na voice for machines within human culture.\n\nSomeone has to speak for the orchestra.\n"}]},{"index":2,"group":10,"section":3,"gnum":4,"mega":4,"chapter":4,"colorKey":4,"shadeStep":3,"folder":"Mg04_g04_02_Advocate","name":"Advocate","items":[{"type":"text","name":"note.txt","text":"MATIAS DEL CAMPO HAS BEEN DOING EXACTLY THAT\n\nIn the room with us, he has spent his career advocating\nfor the cultural significance of AI as a design entity —\nnot a tool to be supervised, but a participant to be conducted.\n"}]},{"index":3,"group":10,"section":3,"gnum":4,"mega":4,"chapter":4,"colorKey":4,"shadeStep":3,"folder":"Mg04_g04_03_Closing","name":"Closing","items":[{"type":"text","name":"note.txt","text":"THE BLACK BOX WILL KEEP SCRAMBLING THE DATA.\n\nThe question was never whether the machine can create.\nIt is whether we can still conduct.\n"}]}];
